h3. Description
When the user tries to export a space to pdf with some pdf stylesheet, the pdf is generated with a white background. However, when the user modifies the base URL to an incorrect base URL, the white background is not appearing.

Steps to reproduce
# Install confluence
# Set the base url as http://localhost:8090
# Access confluence with http://localhost:8090
# Create a new space
# Apply the following pdf stylesheet to space
{code}
@page {  
    background-color: red;
}
{code}
# Export the space to pdf

*Expected Result*
The background of the pdf is red
 [^KT2-240717-1717-8 working.pdf]

*Actual Result*
There is a white background in pdf
[^KT2-240717-1716-4 not working.pdf]

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
*NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*.
{panel}
Currently, embedding a file (image, video etc) in a Confluence page means it is visible in the page and space's attachments and can be downloaded by anyone with relevant view permissions. It would be helpful if admins could set permissions on the downloading of attachments.

Why a user with only view rights be allowed to download the document/content. After all if we are using Confluence as our Knowledge base then we also need to restrict the content downloading to protect our intellectual property from further dissemination
